        "text": {
          "headline": "Describing the lands and people of India Orientalis",
          "text": "<p>This map of <i>India\nOrientalis</i>\nby\nGerman cartographer Lorenz Fries includes information based on an earlier 1507\nworld map composed by Martin Waldseemüller.\nThat map, in turn, drew on accounts of Marco Polo’s 1290 voyage through the\nregion as he returned to Europe from China. [3]</p>\n\n<p></p>\n\n<p>Historian Thomas Suarez describes this\nmap as a “cartographical landmark” because it isolates the area we\ntoday call Southeast Asia as a distinct entity. [4]&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The map includes Latin text describing\nfeatures of the territories. Click on the pins to see what it says.</p>"
        },
        "type": "overview"
      },
      {
        "date": "",
        "text": {
          "headline": "Seylam: Colonial Ceylon, now Sri Lanka.",
          "text": "<p>“This island is one of the largest and\nbest of the world. This island has a very rich king who is tributary to no one.\nThe men of this island are all idolaters and go about nude; they have no grain\nexcept rice, and they have precious stones.”</p>\n\n<p></p>\n\n<p>The term “idolator” had a more general\nmeaning than today, referring to those who worshipped idols or were thought to\nbe pagan.</p>"
        },
